sv:property.sv:value: This page lists some of Magnolia 2.1's more visible new features. For a complete list check the release notes and change log in jira.

Magnolia 2.1 comes with an innovative browser-based interface that works very much like your desktop software. Context sensitive menus let you choose between available actions, double click on items lets you edit them in place and many elements can be manipulated through drag & drop. The Magnolia interface is very easy to use and reduces training to a minimum.

Release 2.1 includes a choice of two leading cross-browser Rich Text Editors - Kup and fckEdit. This makes it very easy to add links, bold or italic text, add numbered and unnumbered lists as well as a host of other features that you'd expect from a rich text editor.  Editing web content is as easy as writing with your favourite word processor - absolutely no html knowledge is necessary to keep your site up to date.

The Magnolia cache is serving pages more than twice as fast as a standard web server serves a static page. We cache pages compressed and uncompressed. This saves the time needed to compress a page, which in turn makes Magnolia faster than your good old static html pages.
Compression is configurable per MIME-type. This allows us for instance to leave images untouched (jpeg or gif are already compressed formats and further compression would slow things down).
You can also configure exactly which pages or site trees you wish to have cached. We use pattern matching on the request. Since images are served with an extra request, this allows us to cache a page but still have a dynamically generated image for each request - for example a page counter.
Twice as Fast as Static Web Pages

Magnolia 2.1 corresponds to the latest JSR-170 specification v1.0 as available through Apache's open source implementation, now called "Jackrabbit".  For higher demands, you have the option to deploy Magnolia Power Pack, a high-end commercial repository implementation, available from the Magnolia Organization.
Featuring latest JSR-170 support using Jackrabbit or Magnolia Power Pack

Magnolia 2.1 can be completely configured through the browser thanks to the new configuration editor. This eliminates the need to drop to the command line to configure your system. In addition, any content can now be activated between instances, including configuration, users, and roles.

One of the most requested feature has been the possibility to deploy Magnolia under one instance, which is now possible. A single J2EE container like tomcat or JBOSS can host as many Magnolia instances as you wish. In particular, you can now have public and author instance in the same container, reducing hosting costs.
Single Container Deployment for easier hosting

Magnolia has been modularized and a new module interface allows you to add custom modules to Magnolia without touching the Magnolia core. The module interface allows:
  • repository sharing
  • local configuration
  • virtual URI mapping
Modules may have their own repositories or access shared repositories. To this end, a new repository loader lets you add module repositories dynamically. Modules can be configured completely through the new configuration editor in adminCentral.

Magnolia sports native search through all content stored inside your repository. Instantly include search into your website thanks to the new search-tag. Updated sample templates provide search functionality out-of-the-box.

Magnolia's outstanding user interface is now even easier to use, thanks to the fact that it speaks your language. 14 languages are already available, including English, Chinese, Russian, French, German, Spanish and Portuguese. You can easily add other languages.
Internationalization - Magnolia now in 14 major languages

We have set up an issue tracker. If you use Magnolia and find a bug, make sure its a bug (and not simply a configuration issue), check the issue tracker if it has been reported before, and add it if no one else has done so. A good bug description needs at least the following information:
  1. state what did you do to make things go wrong (this must be reproducable or else your bug will most likely be resolved with a "works for me" resolution). It should also include relevant background information like what system you are running on.
  2. state what you expect to happen
  3. state what happens instead
If you don't know if something is a bug or a configuration problem, check the mailing list archives for similar problems. If in doubt, post it on the list, and if the general agreement is that its a bug, go add it to the issue tracker.

We welcome your feedback. If you find that Magnolia lacks a feature, add an issue to our issue tracker. Mark your issue as "New feature" if it is something that does not currently exist, and as "improvement" if it exists but could be better. You have to create an account to be able to post issues, which has the advantage that you can receive feedback on th issues you have entered.

If you want to develop web-sites with Magnolia, feel free to subscribe to the Magnolia user mailing list. Simply send an empty email. You can cancel at any time. To subscribe send a mail to: user-list-subscribe@magnolia.info To post send mails to: user-list@magnolia.info Please note the following: to subscribe send a mail to: user-list-subscribe@magnolia.info to post send mails to: user-list@magnolia.info
  • We only accept plain text email on this list. If you are a windows user, by default that requirement will not be met. Please read "Configuring Mail Clients to Send Plain ASCII Text" to understand what is wrong with non-ASCII mail and what you can do about it. Even if that is the only thing you get out of visiting magnolia.info, it will be worth it.
  • Please be sure to check the archive first. Your mail might not  get answered if it has been answered before.
  • Trim your replies. That means do not simply hit "Reply" and start typing. Remove anything that is not directly relevant to your reply before you start typing. We all have the previous mail in our inbox, there is no need to have the whole thread copied into each reply.
  • Be concise - provide as much detail as necessary and as little as possible to state your case.
  • If you want to get the most out of the mailing list, take the time to read asking smart questions, a great article by Eric S. Raymond. Its the best article on the web about asking questions on mailing lists bar none.
  • Keep in mind that all information and answers are provided by volunteers. Commercial support packages are available through partners of the Magnolia partner network.
You can unsubscribe at any time by sending an empty email to user-list-off@magnolia.info To switch to the DIGEST mode, send an empty email to user-list-digest@magnolia.info To switch to the INDEX mode, send an empty email to user-list-index@magnolia.info For any administrative enquieries, please use user-list-request@magnolia.info

Magnolia is the free, open source, J2EE deployable content management system software (CMS) developed by obinary. Magnolia uses the upcoming standard API for java content repositories (JCR) (JSR-170) to access its content. It has an easy to use web-browser interface, a clear API and a useful custom tag library for easy templating in JSP and Servlets.
